{"version":"1.2","person":{"datePublished":"2023-09-13","name":"Reiner Fleming II","nameForms":[{"lang":"en","fullText":"Reiner Fleming II","parts":[{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Given","value":"Reiner"},{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Surname","value":"Fleming"},{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Suffix","value":"II"}],"order":"EUROTYPIC"}],"gender":"Male","lifespan":"1140–1205","fullLifespan":"Abt 1140–Bef 1205","birthDate":"+1140","birthPlace":{"address":"Yorkshire, England","geo":{"latitude":53.95878,"longitude":-1.08248,"@type":"GeoCoordinates"},"@type":"Place"},"deathPlace":{"address":"Yorkshire, England","geo":{"latitude":53.95878,"longitude":-1.08248,"@type":"GeoCoordinates"},"@type":"Place"},"userCertifiedLifeSummary":"«b»Biography«/b»\n\"Before 1166, Reiner Fleming II., son of William, had succeeded to the property [Wath]. This Reiner was head of the family from about 1165-2000. In 1168, he held only 1 1/2 Knight's fee of Skipton castle, so perhaps the lands at Clifton on Calder were only given to the family during his lifetime, and like his father, he gave part of it as a thank-offering to God. For this Reiner, son of William Fleming, founded the Cistercian Nunnery of Kirkleys on his new estates near Mirfield on the Calder, where the nuns seem to have been already living before he gave his undated charter of perhaps 1175-1185, thus: -\n\nTo all sons of Holy Mother the Church, Reiner Fleming, son of William Fleming. Greeting... Be it known to ye all that I have granted in free and perpetual alms to God and to St. Mary and to the nonnes of Kirkales the place in which they remayne, to wit, Kirkelay and Hednesley, as the water of Kelder goes to the old myll...\n\netc., and to the spacious boundaries are all given round by 'Wageston' (or Walter Cross) to Mirfield.\"\n\n\"Reiner, the son of William le Fleming, founded the Benedectine nunnery of Kirklees, in the reign of Henry II.: and this probably the same Reiner le Fleming who is returned one of the tenants of the honour 